FoglieLe leaves are needle-like, thin and slender; blue-green color, can be up to 15 cm long and are collected in groups of five, brought on the branches hairy, yellow-brown.
The fruits are yellow-brown and have a cylindrical shape. They are about 15 cm long and pendulous; they are also rather resinous. The seeds are long, about 6-8 mm and a wing length of about 2 cm.
Distribution and habitatIl white pine mexican is especially widespread in Mexico (in the states of Guerrero, Oaxaca, Chiapas, and Veracruz) and Guatemala but also in Honduras and El Salvador.
It is a tree of the mountains that grows in sunny areas and relatively wet with moderate rainfall in summer, although populations of the eastern and southern parts are located in areas more humid. Requires well drained soils. It tolerates climates, subtropical and temperate.
Impiego√à grown as an ornamental plant but also for commercial purpose for the paper industry in various parts of the world, in all areas (tropical to temperate: on the mountains of Kenya, Tanzania and Angola, south Africa, in the south of Brazil, in the north of India, in Argentina, Australia, and New Zealand. In the British Isles and the United States is grown only as an ornamental, and can be found in parks and gardens. There are several subspecies and varieties.
Although it is native to areas of purely tropical (because its distribution range is located entirely to the south of the Tropic of Cancer) is able to tolerate temperatures decidedly low.
It is a tree moderately sensitive to the parasitic fungus Cronatrium ribicola, although it is more resistant to it than other conifers of the north american continent.
